@node Flags<3>,Toggles<2>,,What FLAGS TOGGLES POWERS DEPOWERS and BITLEVELS mean in RhostMUSH
@anchor{toggles flags}@anchor{e2}
@section Flags


Flags are pretty much exactly the same as any other mush.  It’s a flag
that you set or unset on a target which then enables/disables or
alters something that target can do.  There’s help on all the flags
in help and wizhelp.

@node Toggles<2>,@@power,Flags<3>,What FLAGS TOGGLES POWERS DEPOWERS and BITLEVELS mean in RhostMUSH
@anchor{toggles toggles}@anchor{e3}
@section Toggles


Toggles were designed as a single point flag that immediately enables
or disables a set ability or condition, thus a ‘toggle’.  It works
exactly like a flag and was originally designed for two reasons.  To
distinguish from the multi-meaning of a ‘flag’, and because frankly
we ran out of flag space :)

@node @@power,@@depower,Toggles<2>,What FLAGS TOGGLES POWERS DEPOWERS and BITLEVELS mean in RhostMUSH
@anchor{toggles power}@anchor{e4}
@section @@power


A power is similar to a power on other mushes, but unlike them, our
powers are multi-tier.  This means that they can be customized to
empower something at a given bitlevel.  You may empower something
from guildmaster up to councilor level.  There are some powers
with a power level of N/A meaning they are a toggle power granting
an absolute power level as specified in the help for that power.
This requires the INHERIT flag for non-players to inherit powers,
however, a specific object can be granted a power as well.

@node @@depower,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems,@@power,What FLAGS TOGGLES POWERS DEPOWERS and BITLEVELS mean in RhostMUSH
@anchor{toggles depower}@anchor{e5}
@section @@depower


This is the anti-thesis of @@power.  Also, depowers do not require
inheritance.  They also have priority over flags, toggles, and
powers.  You can use depower to remove or lower abilities and
control from a target, even a full wizard (royalty) can be
depowered.

@node Multi-tiered bitlevel systems,Altering bitlevels,@@depower,What FLAGS TOGGLES POWERS DEPOWERS and BITLEVELS mean in RhostMUSH
@anchor{toggles multi-tiered-bitlevel-systems}@anchor{e6}
@section Multi-tiered bitlevel systems


RhostMUSH offers a multi-tier bitlevel system.  They go in order of presidence
You do not have to use all these bits, only use what you want.

@menu
* ghod (#1) <bitlevel 7>: ghod #1 <bitlevel 7>. 
* Immortal(i) <Level 6> - Basically #1: Immortal i <Level 6> - Basically #1. 
* Royalty(W) <Level 5> - FULL wizbit level: Royalty W <Level 5> - FULL wizbit level. 
* Councilor(a) <Level 4> - High wizbit level: Councilor a <Level 4> - High wizbit level. 
* Architect(B) <Level 3> - Middle wizbit level: Architect B <Level 3> - Middle wizbit level. 
* Guildmaster(g) <Level 2> - Lowest wizbit level: Guildmaster g <Level 2> - Lowest wizbit level. 
* Wanderer <bitlevel 0>:: 
* Guest <bitlevel 0 as well>:: 

@end menu

@node ghod #1 <bitlevel 7>,Immortal i <Level 6> - Basically #1,,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles ghod-1-bitlevel-7}@anchor{e7}
@subsection ghod (#1) <bitlevel 7>


This bitlevel can do everything.  Only those who you trust with absolute power should have this.  Period.

@node Immortal i <Level 6> - Basically #1,Royalty W <Level 5> - FULL wizbit level,ghod #1 <bitlevel 7>,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles immortal-i-level-6-basically-1}@anchor{e8}
@subsection Immortal(i) <Level 6> - Basically #1


The only thing this bitlevel can not do is directly effect #1,
set/unset some internal flags/attributes, and set/unset the
immortal flag.  These players can do EVERYTHING else.  Treat
this bit as you would treat #1.  Only give it to those you know
without a doubt you can trust.


@itemize *

@item 
Can do everything except set some internal flags, effect #1, and set/remove the immortal flag.
@end itemize

@node Royalty W <Level 5> - FULL wizbit level,Councilor a <Level 4> - High wizbit level,Immortal i <Level 6> - Basically #1,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles royalty-w-level-5-full-wizbit-level}@anchor{e9}
@subsection Royalty(W) <Level 5> - FULL wizbit level


This is your standard wizard.  They can do everything you’re
used to on other mushes that wizards can do.  In addition, they
also override all locks by default (this can be disabled), and
they have an enhanced wizcloaking ability (which also can be
disabled).  They can also set all the lower bitlevels.


@itemize *

@item 
All things of Level 4 and lower

@item 
Ability to set more flags: STOP, NOSTOP, FUBAR

@item 
Ability to @@attribute,

@item 
Ability to WIZCLOAK
@end itemize

@node Councilor a <Level 4> - High wizbit level,Architect B <Level 3> - Middle wizbit level,Royalty W <Level 5> - FULL wizbit level,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles councilor-a-level-4-high-wizbit-level}@anchor{ea}
@subsection Councilor(a) <Level 4> - High wizbit level


This is your almost-but-not-quite wizard.  They have access to
about 80% of the wizard commands.  This includes @@nuke, @@toad,
@@newpassword and the like.  The only things they can’t do that
wizards can is cloak, override locks, and use some of the
database manipulation tools in wizhelp.


@itemize *

@item 
All things of Level 3 and lower

@item 
Ability to set more flags: NOCONNECT, WANDERER, FREE

@item 
Ability to @@nuke, @@toad, @@boot, @@chownall, @@dbck, @@poor, @@newpassword, @@pcreate, slay
@end itemize

@node Architect B <Level 3> - Middle wizbit level,Guildmaster g <Level 2> - Lowest wizbit level,Councilor a <Level 4> - High wizbit level,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles architect-b-level-3-middle-wizbit-level}@anchor{eb}
@subsection Architect(B) <Level 3> - Middle wizbit level


This is your sub-wizard.  They still have the ability to control
anything their bitlevel and lower (including @@chown, @@destroy, etc)
but do not have any control of other players (like @@nuke, @@toad, etc)
but they can set the slave flag.  Otherwise, all things their level
and lower they can treat as if they owned it.


@itemize *

@item 
All things of Level 2

@item 
Ability to fully control and modify anything their level and lower (including @@cloning, @@destroying, etc)

@item 
Ability to use @@tel on anything their level and lower.

@item 
Ability to bypass jump_ok rooms on anything their level & lower.

@item 
Ability to set some restricted flags: SLAVE, NO_YELL

@item 
Has infinite quota and money

@item 
Able to give negative money (Steal)

@item 
Able to @@toggle the MONITOR
@end itemize

@node Guildmaster g <Level 2> - Lowest wizbit level,Wanderer <bitlevel 0>,Architect B <Level 3> - Middle wizbit level,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles guildmaster-g-level-2-lowest-wizbit-level}@anchor{ec}
@subsection Guildmaster(g) <Level 2> - Lowest wizbit level


This is the lowest wiz bit.  They only have moderate abilities.
They can examine/decompile anything their level and lower, they can
@@guild/@@quota people, and they have a few other minor abilities.
They don’t have free money however.


@itemize *

@item 
Ability to access things remotely (long_fingers)

@item 
Things are FREE for them in the queue.

@item 
Can see dbref#’s of things their level and lower

@item 
Can examine/decompile things their level and lower.

@item 
Can set @@quota/@@guild on their level and lower.
@end itemize

@node Wanderer <bitlevel 0>,Guest <bitlevel 0 as well>,Guildmaster g <Level 2> - Lowest wizbit level,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles wanderer-bitlevel-0}@anchor{ed}
@subsection Wanderer <bitlevel 0>


This is a hinderance flag.  This flag is automatically set on new
players that are created (which can be disabled).  This flag stops
the player from creating/destroying any database information.   In
effect it stops them from any type of building type commands.  They
still are allowed to set/unset locks/attributes/etc though without
hinderance.

@node Guest <bitlevel 0 as well>,,Wanderer <bitlevel 0>,Multi-tiered bitlevel systems
@anchor{toggles guest-bitlevel-0-as-well}@anchor{ee}
@subsection Guest <bitlevel 0 as well>


This is a bigger hinderance flag.  By default all guests should be
set this.  This flag stops the player from ANY database manipulation
along with @@teleporting, and many other advanced commands.  It’s
extreamly dehibilatating.

